of various work processes we are often not aware of. What is the day-to-day reality for workers in various parts of the world, and how was it in the past? How do they work today, and how did they work in the past? These and many other questions comprise the field of the global history of work - a young discipline that is introduced with this handbook. In 8 thematic chapters, this book discusses these aspects of work in a global and long term perspective, paying attention to several kinds of work. Convict labour, slave and wage labour, labour migration, and workers of the textile industry, but also workers' organisation, strikes, and motivations for work are part of this first handbook of global labour history, written by the most renowned scholars of the profession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aWorkxHistoryvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aWorkxMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 4aArbeit. 4aArbeitsbeziehungen. 4aGlobalgeschichte. 4aHistoriographie. 7aHISTORY / Reference.2bisacsh1 aKnotter, Ad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomlosy, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreund, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Bryan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Vito, Christian G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoll-Murata, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoris, Eileen, econtributor.